88 2004 ISBN: 1405103213 Publication Date: 2005-01-03          Understanding Digital Humanities by David M. Berry (Editor) Call Number: AZ105 .U64 2012eb ISBN: 023029264X Publication Date: 2012-03-15  ebrary Available only to UIC users              Further Introductory Readings     The following pages and articles provide an introduction to the field of digital humanities and its evolution/development over time:    What is DH?  Digital Humanities@UCLA    Teaching DH: Readings  University of Texas iSchool   more...  less...   This page, part of University of Texas' iSchool blog on teaching DH, presents a list of helpful readings meant to introduce readers to DH. The majority of the readings were written in 2011, but older pieces are also included. This list largely focuses on resources relating to DH in the classroom, but begins with a section devoted to the definition and history of DH.   It also includes a link to a readings' list put together by prominent Digital Humanist Lisa Spiro.    What's "Digital Humanities" and How Did It Get Here?  John Unsworth, Brandeis University, 2012    Transitioning to a Digital World: Art History, Its Research Centers, and Digital Scholarship  Diane M. Zorich. Kress Foundation sponsored survey of the art history community. 2012    Introducing the Digital Humanities  Korey Jackson and Aaron McCollough, University of Michigan. 2011   more...  less...   An interactive presentation created for a workshop at University of Michigan's Teaching and Technology Collaborative. Further background here .    Humanities 3.0: Tooling Up for Digital Humanities  Stanford University. 2011.    What Skills Are Needed for the Digital Humanities?  Kathryn Greenhill and Kate Davis, Curtin University / Queensland University of Technology, Australia. 2011    What is Humanities Computing and What's It Doing in English Departments?  Matthew G. Kirschenbaum, Maryland Institute for Technology in the Humanities, University of Maryland. 2010    The Landscape of Digital Humanities  Patrik Svensson,  HUMlab, Umeå University. 2010    A Day in the Life of Digital Humanities  University of Alberta. 2009-present.   more...  less...   A Day in the Life of the Digital Humanities (Day of DH) is a community publication project that attempts to answer the question, "What does a digital humanist do?" On Day of DH, once a year, participants document their day through photographs and commentary in a blog-like journal, which is then made available online. As part of the project participants are also asked to contribute their own perspectives on the definition of digital humanities.    The Digital Humanities Manifesto 2.0  Jeffrey Schnapp and Peter Lunenfeld, et al. UCLA. 2009    What is Digital Humanities?  Whitney Anne Trettien, Hyperstudio, MIT. 2009    An Agenda for Electronic Text Technology in the Humanities  Susan Hockey, University of Alberta. 1998                 Special Topics in DH            Digital Research in the Study of Classical Antiquity by Gabriel Bodard; Simon Mahony Call Number: DE15 .D54 2010eb ISBN: 9780754695233 Publication Date: 2010-05-01          The Spatial Humanities by David J. Bodenhamer (Editor); John Corrigan (Editor); Trevor M. Harris (Editor) Call Number: G70.212 .S654 2010 ISBN: 9780253222176 Publication Date: 2010-06-28          Designed Maps by Cynthia Brewer Call Number: GA105.3 .B73 2008 ISBN: 9781589481602 Publication Date: 2008-03-01          A Companion to Digital Literary Studies by Ray Siemens (Editor); Susan Schreibman (Editor) Call Number: PN56.I65 C66 2007eb ISBN: 9781405148641 Publication Date: 2008-01-22          William Blake and the Digital Humanities by Jason Whittaker; Roger Whitson Call Number: PR4148.I52 W46 2013 ISBN: 9780415656184 Publication Date: 2012-12-19          The American Literature Scholar in the Digital Age by Amy Earhart; Andrew Jewell Call Number: PS51 .A64 2011 ISBN: 9780472051199 Publication Date: 2010-12-29  Also available as an e-book.              DH in Libraries   